solution.p:
We will evaluate the total population by writing

\sum_{n=1}^{2 \times 10^6}\frac{2\times 10^6}{n}
=\sum_{n=1}^{a-1}\frac{2\times 10^6}{n}
+\sum_{n=a}^{2 \times 10^6}\frac{2\times 10^6}{n}

and applying the above integral approximations to the second sum.
We want our error to be less than one million, so we need to choose a value of a such that:

	\underbrace{2\times 10^6\int_{a-1}^{2\times 10^6} \frac{1}{x}\dee{x}}_{\text{upper bound}} -
	\underbrace{2\times 10^6\int_{a}^{2\times 10^6+1} \frac{1}{x}\dee{x}}_{\text{lower bound}} & \lt 10^6

\int_{a-1}^{2\times 10^6} \frac{1}{x}\dee{x} -
	\int_{a}^{2\times 10^6+1} \frac{1}{x}\dee{x} & \lt \frac{1}{2}

	\left[\log\left(2\times 10^6 \right)-\log(a-1)\right]-\left[\log\left(2\times 10^6+1 \right)-\log(a)\right]& \lt \frac12

	\left[\log\left(2\times 10^6 \right)-\log\left(2\times 10^6+1 \right)\right]+\left[ \log(a)-\log(a-1)\right]& \lt \frac12

	\log\left(\frac{2\times 10^6}{2\times 10^6+1} \right)+
	\log\left(\frac{a}{a-1} \right)& \lt \frac{1}{2}


	The first term is extremely close to 0, so we ignore it.


	\log\left(\frac{a}{a-1} \right)& \lt \frac{1}{2}

	\frac{a}{a-1}& \lt e^{1/2}=\sqrt{e}

	a& \lt a\sqrt{e}-\sqrt{e}

	\sqrt{e}& \lt a(\sqrt{e}-1)

	\frac{\sqrt{e}}{\sqrt{e}-1}& \lt a


	Since \dfrac{\sqrt{e}}{\sqrt{e}-1} \approx 2.5, we use a=3. That is, we will approximate the value of \displaystyle\sum_{n=3}^{2\times 10^6}\frac{1}{n} using an integral. Then, we will use that approximation to estimate our total population.

\int_3^{2\times 10^6+1}\frac{1}{x}\dee{x}& \lt \sum_{n=3}^{2\times 10^6}\frac{1}{n} 
                                 \lt \int_2^{2\times10^6}\frac{1}{x}\dee{x}


\log\left(2\times 10^6+1\right)-\log(3) & \lt \sum_{n=3}^{2\times 10^6}\frac{1}{n} 
                               \lt \log\left(2\times10^6\right)-\log(2)


\textcolor{red}{1+\frac12}+\log\left(2\times 10^6+1\right)-\log(3) 
              &  \lt \sum_{n=\textcolor{red}{1}}^{2\times 10^6}\frac{1}{n}  
               \lt \textcolor{red}{1+\frac12}+\log\left(2\times10^6\right)
\amp\hskip2in-\log(2)


\frac32+ \log\left(\frac{2\times 10^6+1}{3}\right) 
                 & \lt \sum_{n=1}^{2\times 10^6}\frac{1}{n} 
                   \lt \frac32+6\log(10)


So the population, namely 
 \sum_{n=1}^{2\times 10^6}\frac{\textcolor{red}{2\times10^6}}{n}, is between

\textcolor{red}{2\times10^6}\Big(\frac32+ \log\left(\tfrac{2}{3}\times 10^6+\tfrac{1}{3}\right)\Big)=29,820,091

and

\textcolor{red}{2\times10^6}\Big(\frac32+6\log\left(10\right)\Big)=30,631,021
